<subSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="multiple">
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,429,217,241]" box="[192,429,217,241]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<heading bold="true" box="[192,429,217,241]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,429,217,241]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Nesting behavior</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
The nests were built in a shaded vertical bank, consisting of a white clay-like substrate, which was very loose. Other 
<taxonomicName box="[410,581,298,322]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
, including the bees 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fabricius)" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[827,1211,297,322]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Anthophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tricolor">
<emphasis box="[827,1069,297,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Anthophora tricolor</emphasis>
(Fabricius)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1274,1440,297,321]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1274,1440,297,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Lasioglossum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. and the wasp 
<taxonomicName box="[405,464,330,353]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Liris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[405,464,330,353]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Liris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp., nested in this area.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
Females of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pate" authorityYear="1937" box="[376,459,362,385]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[376,459,362,385]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Xysma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
constantly overflew the nesting area, keeping their body almost vertical (with the metasoma down), with zigzag movements before entering the nest. They generally landed a few centimeters from the entrance before walking inside, although at other times they flew in directly. The females remained inside the nests when resting and perhaps during the night. There was internal closure, made with soil, during the time that females remained inside the nest.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Females grabbed the prey with their mandibles, holding them by one of the forelegs or neck, with the ventral region facing upwards. The prey consisted of immature thrips (Thysanoptera).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
The average diameter of the entrance was 
<quantity box="[766,858,586,610]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
(n=8, range=2.0– 
<quantity box="[1077,1173,587,611]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
, SD=0.5). Nests were short, with an approximate depth of 
<quantity box="[639,696,619,643]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="cm" value="3.0">3 cm</quantity>
(n=4), with the entrance on the same plane as the substrate. The absence of a foretarsal rake and pygidial plate means that females are poorly equipped for digging, but in this case the friable substrate perhaps facilitated excavation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
Due to a shortage of time and the difficulty of digging in this substrate, little attention was paid to the excavation of the nests without knowing the number of cells they possibly contained. Cocoons were stuck to the substrate, and usually observed attached together (in twos, threes and sometimes fours) (
<figureCitation box="[201,273,811,835]" captionStart="Figures 1–7" captionStartId="6.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[242,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[241,1392,213,1815]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 1–7. Xysma dominicum Antropov. 1–2) Face (in frontal view). 1) Female. 2) Male. 3) Mesosoma of the male (in dorsal view). 4–5) Habitus images. 4) Female. 5) Male. 6) Illustrations of the fore- and hindwings. 7) Emerged cocoons obtained from nests." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3674911" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3674911/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Cocoon size ranged from 
<quantity box="[600,766,811,835]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.95" metricValueMax="3.1" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="mm" value="2.95" valueMax="3.1" valueMin="2.8">2.8 to 3.1 mm</quantity>
(x=3.0 mm, SD=0.1, n=5).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
It seems that the females covered the cells with some substance, likely silk; it is known that other members of the subtribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Menke" authorityYear="1989" box="[493,651,876,900]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Spilomenina">Spilomenina</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1838" box="[661,916,875,900]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Spilomena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[661,792,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Spilomena</emphasis>
Shuckard
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="F. Smith" authorityName="F. Smith" box="[930,1215,875,900]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Arpactophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[930,1102,875,899]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Arpactophilus</emphasis>
F. Smith
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ducke" authorityName="Ducke" authorityYear="1907" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Microstigmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1274,1440,876,899]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Microstigmus</emphasis>
Ducke
</taxonomicName>
use silk in nesting (
<bibRefCitation author="Matthews, R. W. &amp; I. D. Naumann" box="[516,894,908,932]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="101 - 133" refId="ref3020" refString="Matthews, R. W., and I. D. Naumann 2002. Descriptions and biology of nine new species of Arpactophilus (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae), with a key to described Australian species. Journal of Hymenoptera Research 11: 101 - 133." type="journal article" year="2002">Matthews and Naumann 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
Species of subtribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Menke" authorityYear="1989" box="[471,625,940,964]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Spilomenina">Spilomenina</taxonomicName>
(of which 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pate" authorityYear="1937" box="[754,837,940,963]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[754,837,940,963]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Xysma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also a member) are of considerable interest as they include some of the few apoid wasps that exhibit a high degree of social behavior and because adult females are able to spin silk from specialized setae on the sixth tergum, which they use in nest construction (
<bibRefCitation author="Melo, G. A. R." box="[359,489,1036,1060]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 9" refId="ref3068" refString="Melo, G. A. R. 1997. Silk glands in adult sphecid wasps (Hymenoptera, Sphecidae, Pemphredoninae). Journal of Hymenoptera Research 6: 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="1997">Melo 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Serrao, J. E. &amp; L. A. de Oliveira" box="[501,848,1036,1060]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="479 - 486" refId="ref3323" refString="Serrao, J. E., and L. A. de Oliveira. 2000. Notes on the structure of silk glands in sphecid wasps, Microstigmus and Psenulus (Hymenoptera, Sphecidae, Pemphredoninae). Netherlands Journal of Zoology 50: 479 - 486." type="journal article" year="2000">Serrão and de Oliveira 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ohl, M. &amp; D. J. Bennett" box="[859,1133,1036,1060]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="145 - 150" refId="ref3102" refString="Ohl, M., and D. J. Bennett. 2009. A new genus and species of apoid wasps from Saxonian amber (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Crabronidae). Denisia 26, zugleich Kataloge der oberosterreichischen Landesmuseen Neue Serie 86: 145 - 150." type="journal article" year="2009">Ohl and Bennett 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Breitkreuz, L. C. V. &amp; M. Ohl &amp; M. S. Engel" box="[1145,1417,1036,1060]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 66" refId="ref2817" refString="Breitkreuz, L. C. V., M. Ohl, and M. S. Engel. 2016. A review of the New Caledonian Arpactophilus (Hymenoptera: Crabronidae). Zootaxa 4063 (1): 1 - 66." type="journal article" year="2016">Breitkreuz et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,266,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
These observations are consistent with what little has been published on the nesting behavior of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pate" authorityYear="1937" box="[192,275,1101,1124]" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Xysma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[192,275,1101,1124]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Xysma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="Krombein, K. V." box="[383,576,1100,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="21 - 26" refId="ref2984" refString="Krombein, K. V. 1958. Miscellaneous prey records of solitary wasps. III. (Hymenoptera, Aculeata). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 71: 21 - 26." type="journal article" year="1958">Krombein 1958</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bohart, R. M. &amp; A. S. Menke" box="[587,887,1100,1124]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" refId="ref2781" refString="Bohart, R. M., and A. S. Menke. 1976. Sphecid wasps of the world: a generic revision. University of California Press; Berkeley. 695 p." type="book" year="1976">Bohart and Menke 1976</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
